# Air Boltic

# Analytics Architecture.

## **20th June 2025**							      *Author: **Marco Gonzalez**.*

# **OVERVIEW**

The Analytics Architecture for Air Boltic is designed to support **reliable**, **accurate**, **consistent**, and **timely monitoring**, while **enabling self-service analysis** at a scale that aligns with Bolt’s ambition to serve up to 20% of global airplane rides by 2030\.

The data model emphasizes flexibility and **maintainability**, allowing for evolving business definitions and seamless expansion as new use cases emerge.

To ensure a **high-quality experience for diverse data users** \- including Business Analysts, Product Managers, Data Scientists, Operations Managers, Executives, and Engineers \- the architecture incorporates:

* Comprehensive documentation of models, columns, and key metrics.  
* Version control for traceability and safe iteration.  
* Clear sharing and governance practices, aligned with industry best standards for reliability, scalability, and usability.

# **ANALYTICAL GOALS**

To support Bolt’s ambition of facilitating 20% of global airplane rides by 2030 and ensure that Air Boltic aligns with the company’s broader mobility portfolio, our data models will specifically support analysis in three key areas, each area considers both the demand side (passengers) and the supply side (airplane operators).

* **Growth Drivers** \- What fuels platform adoption and repeat use. On the demand side, this includes tracking referral sources, acquisition channels, time to first booking, repeat behavior, and route diversity. These help evaluate acquisition effectiveness, activation timing, and user engagement. On the supply side, growth is measured through the number of active operators, their onboarding rate, fleet expansion, and regional availability \- factors that directly affect trip availability and demand capture.  
* **Performance Metrics** \- Monitor the operational health of the platform. On the demand side, this includes trip completion rates, on-time departure and arrival, booking lead times, cancellation rate and time, and usage frequency. On the supply side, we track aircraft utilization, idle fleet capacity, operator responsiveness, and time to trip confirmation \- a key indicator of reliability and user satisfaction. Together, these metrics help surface bottlenecks, inefficiencies, and service quality issues.  
* **Strategic Insights** \- Guide longer-term decisions and platform scaling. On the demand side, this includes profitability and retention by customer segment, behavioral trends across cohorts, and how Air Boltic usage overlaps with Bolt’s other services. On the supply side, strategic models assess operator-level reliability, route coverage, and revenue concentration \- helping manage risk exposure and inform decisions around operator incentives, partnerships, or regional scaling priorities. These insights collectively support sustainable growth, balanced supply-demand dynamics, and alignment with Bolt’s broader mobility strategy.

# **SPECIFICATIONS \- PART 1**

To meet our analytical goals and support self-service data exploration, the pipeline will produce three clearly defined analytical domains: **Growth**, **Performance**, and **Strategy**. Each domain will contain a set of **business-facing models** (marts) designed to surface the insights outlined in the corresponding goal areas. These models will serve as the foundation for high-impact analyses, ensuring that key metrics and behaviors are readily accessible, reliable, and consistently defined across the organization.

The data models will be implemented using **dbt**, following the standard layered structure [recommended by dbt Labs](https://docs.getdbt.com/best-practices/how-we-structure/1-guide-overview) \- progressing from **Seeds** and **Sources** (raw inputs), through **Staging** and **Intermediate** layers, and culminating in **Marts** (business-ready outputs).

### **Mart Layer**

**Growth Domain** \- This domain captures user behavior and platform growth, including acquisition, activation, and engagement over time.

* **FCT\_PASSENGER** \- behavioral metrics and growth indicators for individual demand-side users (passengers)  
* **DIM\_PASSENGER** \- Enriched attributes about passengers (signup channel, home market, preferred routes, cohort)  
* **FCT\_ORDER** \- Captures booking events, measuring demand-side activation, conversion, and monetization behavior.  
* **FCT\_OPERATOR** \- Captures activity, responsiveness, and supply-side contribution to platform growth.  
* **DIM\_OPERATOR** \- Static and descriptive info on each operator (signup date, home base, fleet size, segment)

**Performance Domain** \- This domain measures operational quality and efficiency, including how reliably trips are completed and how well capacity is utilized.

* **FCT\_TRIP** \- The core model capturing the operational status and quality of each trip.  
* **FCT\_ROUTE** \- Aggregates operational performance per route (airport pair).  
* **DIM\_ROUTE** \- Describes airport-to-airport routes, enabling aggregation of performance and capacity metrics by corridor. Includes route type and geography.  
* **FCT\_CAPACITY** \- Measures how efficiently aircraft capacity is being used across the platform.  
* **FACT\_AIRCRAFT** \- how individual planes are contributing to supply-side growth, operations, and capacity planning.  
* **DIM\_AIRCRAFT** \- Enriched info on aircraft (model, seat capacity, operator ID, age, usage classification)

**Strategy Domain** \- This domain supports strategic decision-making by surfacing market-level financials, cohort performance, and segment-specific engagement and monetization.

* **FCT\_PLATFORM** \- All-in-one strategic model tracking the performance of the business at the market, time, and cohort level.  
* **DIM\_MARKET** \- Defines geographical markets (region, country, operating zone)

### **Intermediate Layer**

### **Staging Layer**

* **STG\_ORDER \-** Checks for null values, negative prices and non standard status labels, standardizes column names.  
* **STG\_TRIP \-** Checks for null values, parses timestamp columns, standardizes column names.  
* **STG\_CUSTOMER \-** Checks for null values, parses phone number, standardizes column names.  
* **STG\_CUSTOMER\_GROUP \-** Checks for null values, standardizes column names.  
* **STG\_AEROPLANE \-** Checks for null values, standardizes column names.

### **Sources and Seeds Layer**

* **`SRC_ORDER`** \- Raw purchase data linking passengers to trips.  
* **`SRC_TRIP`** \- Raw flight data with details such as schedule, aircraft, and airports.  
* **`SRC_CUSTOMER`** \- Basic user information for passengers.  
* **`SRC_CUSTOMER_GROUP`** \- Links customers to group or organizational structures.  
* **`SRC_AEROPLANE`** \- Raw records for aircraft identifiers, model, and manufacturer.  
* **`SEED_AEROPLANE_MODEL`** \- Static reference table for aircraft model specs (e.g., capacity, manufacturer, maximum distance).

### **Scope of implementation**

In order to maximize the level of impact given the time constraints, so far in this iteration only the **FCT\_PASSENGER** model will be implemented along with the models necessary for the selected model to have a logically complete pipeline.

The implementation will be carried out using dbt core as a data transformation engine with the models implemented in sql and the documentation implemented on yml files, for version control git will be used and the implementation will be hosted on github. The ERD representing a high level overview of the implementation will be stored in the repository on Markdown files containing [Mermaid](https://mermaid.js.org/) code.

The github repository with the code as well as any other relevant items for this take home test can be found [here](https://github.com/MrFocusPocus/boltic-air-dbt).

### **Next steps**

If I had more time I would:

* **Implement the rest of the models** to provide a complete look at the “Air Boltic” business.  
* **Integrate external datasets** to provide broader market context — including publicly available global flight data to benchmark Air Boltic activity against global trends, flight density, and route saturation.  
* **Enhance location granularity** by enriching the trip data with airport-level precision rather than city-level, enabling more accurate modeling of routes, hubs, and operational performance.  
* **Model monetization and margins more deeply**, including cost attribution per trip, seat, and route to support profitability analysis and route optimization.  
* **Implement rigorous data quality monitoring** using custom dbt tests, freshness checks, and alerts to ensure trust in data over time.

# **IDEAL FUTURE-PROOF CI/CD \- PART 2**

### **Unlimited Resources**

If resources weren’t a constraint, I would build a data deployment process that’s automated, safe, and easy to trust. Every dbt change would go through a pull request process that spins up a separate environment with a clean copy of the database schema. There, I’d run automated tests — not just to check that models build, but to validate that the data they produce is correct and complete. I’d compare the new results with production using tools that help spot row count changes, column differences, or surprising shifts in metrics. Each model would be owned by someone clearly responsible for keeping it healthy. Once the code passes all checks, it would be merged and deployed in stages (using versioning), so we can monitor the impact before it reaches everyone. To catch future issues early, I’d set up alerts that watch for unusual behavior, like late data loads, missing rows, or model failures and freshnes delay alerts so that data consumers can rest easy that they can trust the data.

### **Real World Constraints**

In more constrained environments like the one I work in now, I’d start with high-leverage, low-friction safeguards: Git-based CI with model-level testing, simple PR review workflows, and clear ownership conventions. At SumUp, for example, we compare the dbt manifest from the feature branch to production, and automatically test all new, modified, and downstream models before merge — this has caught many edge cases without the need for expensive tooling. I’d harden only critical paths (like fct\_orders) with stricter data tests and contracts, and rely on open-source tools like Elementary for lightweight monitoring. Long-term, the biggest gains come from fostering a culture where data is treated like a product — with code standards, testing discipline, and iterative automation driven by friction in the workflow.
